Tom tried to find the derivative of $\dfrac{\sqrt{x}}{x^4}$. Here is his work:

**Step 1:** This is the quotient of $\sqrt x$ and $x^4$. So we should use the quotient rule.

**Step 2:**

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\dfrac{d}{dx} \left[ \dfrac{\sqrt{x}}{x^4} \right]
\\\\
&=\dfrac{\dfrac{d}{dx}[\sqrt{x}]x^4-\sqrt{x}\dfrac{d}{dx}[x^4] }{[x^4]^2}
\end{align}$

**Step 3:** Finding the derivatives of the factors:

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{d}{dx}[\sqrt x]&=0.5x^{-0.5}
\\\\
\dfrac{d}{dx}[x^4]&=4x^3
\end{align}$

**Step 4:** Putting it all together:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\dfrac{d}{dx} \left[ \dfrac{\sqrt{x}}{x^4} \right]
\\\\
&=\dfrac{\dfrac{d}{dx}[\sqrt{x}]x^4-\sqrt{x}\dfrac{d}{dx}[x^4] }{[x^4]^2}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{0.5x^{-0.5}\cdot x^4-x^{0.5}\cdot 4x^3}{x^8}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{-4x^{3.5}+0.5x^{3.5}}{x^8}
\\\\
&=-3.5x^{-4.5}
\end{align}$

**Is Tom's work correct? If not, what's his mistake?**

